    "slug": "realtime-alerts-for-wildfire-safety-r5jkk",
    "title": "Real-Time Alerts for Wildfire Safety",
    "description": "<p>Wildfires are becoming more frequent and more destructive every year. In California alone, millions of people live in fire-prone areas, and the difference between safety and disaster can come down to minutes — sometimes seconds — of warning.</p><p><strong>Watch Duty</strong> is a nonprofit organization that provides free, real-time wildfire alerts to communities across the Western United States. Unlike government alert systems that can be slow or overly broad, Watch Duty uses a network of <em>trained, real firefighters and first responders</em> who monitor fire activity around the clock and push hyper-local notifications directly to your phone.</p><p>Since launching, Watch Duty has delivered over <strong>50 million alerts</strong> and helped countless families evacuate safely. Their reporting is trusted by fire departments, emergency managers, and everyday people who depend on accurate, timely information when it matters most.</p><h3>Why We're Fundraising</h3><p>Watch Duty runs entirely on donations — no ads, no paywalls, no data selling. Every dollar goes toward keeping the platform running: server infrastructure, firefighter stipends for overnight monitoring shifts, and expanding coverage to new at-risk regions.</p><p>Our goal is to raise <strong>$3,000</strong> to directly support Watch Duty's operations during the upcoming fire season. Here's how your donation helps:</p><ul><li><strong>$25</strong> — Covers one hour of a trained monitor's shift</li><li><strong>$100</strong> — Funds server costs for a day of real-time alerting</li><li><strong>$500</strong> — Sponsors monitoring expansion into a new county</li></ul><h3>This Is Personal</h3><p>I started this fundraiser after my own neighborhood in Los Altos received a Watch Duty alert about a brush fire just two miles away. That alert gave my family the time we needed to prepare — pack essentials, check on elderly neighbors, and have an evacuation plan ready. The fire was contained, but the peace of mind was invaluable.</p><p>Please consider donating and sharing this campaign. Every contribution, no matter the size, brings us closer to a future where no one is caught off guard by a wildfire. Together, we can keep our communities safe.</p>",
